B.Um=new A.c("What is the primary difference between Coma and Vegetative State (VS) regarding wakefulness?","Wakefulness (eye opening/sleep-wake cycles) is absent in Coma but present in VS.")
B.Rb=new A.c("In the term 'Unresponsive Wakefulness Syndrome' (UWS), what does 'wakefulness' specifically refer to?","The presence of eye opening.")
B.N5=new A.c("Which classification is defined by minimal but definite evidence of non-reflexive, non-language-dependent behavior?","Minimally Conscious State Minus (MCS-)")
B.Xp=new A.c("What behavior distinguishes MCS+ from MCS-?","Language-mediated behavior (e.g., command following or intelligible verbalization).")
B.Nz=new A.c("What are the two specific criteria for Emergence from MCS?","Functional object use OR functional accurate communication.")
B.Y1=new A.c("To meet the criterion for 'Functional Accurate Communication', how many orientation questions must a patient answer correctly?","6 of 6 correct on two consecutive evaluations.")
B.UA=new A.c("How is 'Persistent VS' defined temporally?","A vegetative state lasting >=1 month after any brain injury.")
B.Y0=new A.c("What is the traditional timeline for diagnosing 'Permanent VS' following a traumatic brain injury (TBI)?","Greater than 12 months post-injury.")
B.a_o=new A.c("What is the traditional timeline for diagnosing 'Permanent VS' following a non-traumatic (anoxic) injury?","Greater than 3 months post-injury.")
B.V2=new A.c("Why is the term 'permanent' increasingly being replaced with 'chronic' in DOC literature?","To reflect that recovery of consciousness beyond traditional timelines is possible, though rare.")
B.U7=new A.c("According to the Multi-Society Task Force, what percentage of traumatic VS patients recover consciousness by 12 months?","Approximately 52%")
B.YL=new A.c("How does the 12-month recovery rate for traumatic VS compare to non-traumatic VS?","Traumatic VS (52%) has a much better prognosis than non-traumatic VS (11-15%).")
B.Zb=new A.c("List three examples of behaviors seen in MCS-.","Visual fixation, visual pursuit, and localization to noxious stimuli.")
B.YU=new A.c("What is the minimum duration for visual fixation to be considered a sign of MCS- on the CRS-R?","Greater than 2 seconds.")
B.X3=new A.c("What is the difference between MCS- and MCS+ regarding functional independence after emergence?","There are no significant differences; functional independence trajectories are comparable once emerged.")
B.Qu=new A.c("Which condition is characterized by full awareness but complete paralysis except for vertical eye movements and blinking?","Locked-In Syndrome (LIS)")
B.Zk=new A.c("What is the most common etiology of Locked-In Syndrome?","Ventral pontine lesion (often due to basilar artery thrombosis).")
B.Xk=new A.c("How does the EEG of a patient in Locked-In Syndrome typically differ from one in Vegetative State?","LIS shows a normal or near-normal alpha rhythm, while VS shows diffuse slowing.")
B.Nl=new A.c("Why is the FOUR Score sometimes preferred over the GCS for identifying Locked-In Syndrome?","The FOUR Score specifically detects eye tracking, which the GCS cannot distinguish from VS.")
B.SZ=new A.c("How many times should the CRS-R be administered to minimize false negatives for consciousness?","At least 5 times.")
B.Pb=new A.c("Why is 'closing eyes to command' considered a risky test for command following in VS?","It may result in a false-positive because patients in VS periodically blink spontaneously.")
B.Ns=new A.c("What score on the CRS-R Auditory Function Scale indicates MCS+?","A score of 3 (reproducible movement to command) or 4 (consistent movement to command).")
B.Nw=new A.c("What is the single most common behavior that distinguishes MCS from VS on the CRS-R?","Visual pursuit (smooth tracking).")
B.XW=new A.c("What stimulus is considered most sensitive for eliciting visual pursuit in DOC patients?","A mirror.")
B.XA=new A.c("On the CRS-R Motor Function Scale, what distinguishes 'localization to noxious stimuli' from 'withdrawal'?","Localization requires the limb to cross the midline or reach above the clavicle to the stimulus.")
B.TS=new A.c("What does a score of 6 on the CRS-R Motor Function subscale signify?","Functional object use (Emergence from MCS).")
B.SW=new A.c("What is the definition of 'Intelligible Verbalization' on the CRS-R Oromotor/Verbal scale?","At least one clearly recognizable word.")
B.PU=new A.c("On the CRS-R, total score is considered less important for diagnosis than _____.","Subscale scores (identifying the highest level of behavior in any domain).")
B.UN=new A.c("Define 'Cognitive Motor Dissociation' (CMD).","Brain activation on fMRI/EEG during cognitive tasks in patients who are behaviorally unresponsive.")
B.W3=new A.c("According to the 2024 NEJM study, what percentage of behaviorally unresponsive DOC patients showed brain activity on task-based fMRI or EEG?","25%")
B.Pq=new A.c("What task is typically used in fMRI motor imagery paradigms to activate the supplementary motor area?","Asking the patient to 'imagine playing tennis'.")
B.a_K=new A.c("In fMRI motor imagery, asking a patient to 'imagine walking through your house' targets which brain area?","Parahippocampal place area")
B.Ws=new A.c("What is the prognostic significance of finding CMD in a behaviorally unresponsive patient?","They are more likely to show functional recovery at 12 months.")
B.TJ=new A.c("Which medication provides the only Level B (Class II) evidence for accelerating recovery from DOC after severe TBI?","Amantadine")
B.ZL=new A.c("What was the treatment window (weeks post-injury) in the landmark 2012 Amantadine trial by Giacino et al.?","4 to 16 weeks post-TBI.")
B.SL=new A.c("What was the starting dose of Amantadine in the Giacino 2012 study?","100 mg BID (200 mg/day).")
B.UC=new A.c("In the Amantadine trial, what happened to the recovery rate of the treatment group during the 2-week washout period?","The rate of recovery slowed significantly compared to the placebo group.")
B.QI=new A.c("What is the primary mechanism of action for Amantadine in TBI?","It releases preformed dopamine from presynaptic terminals and acts as a weak NMDA antagonist.")
B.XT=new A.c("Does current evidence support the use of Amantadine for cognitive recovery in subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH)?","No, a 2024 study found no significant benefit in post-aneurysmal SAH.")
B.XM=new A.c("Which dopaminergic agent is a direct D2 receptor agonist used for executive dysfunction or akinetic mutism?","Bromocriptine")
B.ZN=new A.c("What is the first-line dopaminergic agent for attention deficits in TBI?","Methylphenidate")
B.Yc=new A.c("What percentage of VS/MCS patients exhibit a 'paradoxical response' to Zolpidem?","6-7%")
B.Tz=new A.c("Explain the 'Zolpidem Paradox' mechanism in DOC.","Zolpidem inhibits overactive GPi neurons, which disinhibits the thalamus and restores thalamocortical signaling.")
B.Qx=new A.c("How long does the improved responsiveness typically last after a dose of Zolpidem in responders?","1-4 hours.")
B.Rm=new A.c("Which brain region is the standard target for Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) in DOC?","Left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC).")
B.ZB=new A.c("In tDCS trials, which patient subgroups show the best response?","Patients in MCS (vs VS) and those with traumatic (vs anoxic) etiology.")
B.OZ=new A.c("What is the target for Low-Intensity Focused Ultrasound (LIFU) in DOC treatment?","Central thalamus")
B.XY=new A.c("What does the Perturbational Complexity Index (PCI) measure?","The spatiotemporal EEG response to a TMS pulse, binarized and compressed to estimate algorithmic complexity.")
B.Ql=new A.c("What PCI value threshold is used to discriminate conscious from unconscious states?","Approximately 0.31")
B.a__=new A.c("Which serum biomarker of neuronal decay is highly sensitive and remains elevated for over a year after TBI?","Neurofilament Light Chain (NfL)")
B.VY=new A.c("Elevated serum NfL levels in DOC patients are associated with which consciousness level?","Worse consciousness levels (VS/UWS vs. EMCS).")
B.QN=new A.c("Which glial biomarker reflects astrocytic injury and is elevated in prolonged DOC?","Glial Fibrillary Acidic Protein (GFAP)")
B.QA=new A.c("What is the most reliable electrophysiological predictor of non-recovery in anoxic brain injury?","Bilateral absence of the cortical N20 response on SSEP.")
B.Oz=new A.c("List three favorable prognostic factors for recovery from DOC.","Traumatic etiology, younger age, and presence of CMD (cognitive motor dissociation).")
B.Of=new A.c("What is the primary outcome measure used in the 2012 Amantadine trial?","Disability Rating Scale (DRS)")
B.Va=new A.c("What is the range of the Disability Rating Scale (DRS) and what does a score of 30 represent?","Range 0-30; 30 represents death (0 = no disability).")
B.X0=new A.c("On the Glasgow Outcome Scale (GOS), what does a score of 2 represent?","Persistent vegetative state")
B.Uz=new A.c("Which Rancho Los Amigos Level corresponds to a 'Localized Response'?","Level III")
B.P6=new A.c("Which Rancho Los Amigos Level corresponds to 'Confused and Agitated' (posttraumatic confusional state)?","Level IV")
B.PL=new A.c("According to the 2018 AAN/ACRM guidelines, clinicians should avoid predicting permanent unconsciousness within what timeframe post-injury?","The first 28 days.")
B.XR=new A.c("Why are medications like haloperidol or risperidone generally avoided in early DOC recovery?","They are dopaminergic antagonists that may hinder motor recovery and spatial learning.")
B.PP=new A.c("Name two classes of medications that can cause paradoxical agitation or cognitive slowing in TBI patients.","Benzodiazepines and Anticholinergics.")
B.S5=new A.c("What is the recommended maximum daily dose of Amantadine for DOC, assuming normal renal function?","400 mg/day (200 mg BID).")
B.Tv=new A.c("Which neuroimaging modality is Level B recommended by the AAN 2018 guideline for patients without behavioral command-following?","Task-based fMRI (or EEG).")
B.iy=s([B.Sc,B.Yr,B.R6,B.X2,B.Ww,B.Um,B.Rb,B.N5,B.Xp,B.Nz,B.Y1,B.UA,B.Y0,B.a_o,B.V2,B.U7,B.YL,B.Zb,B.YU,B.X3,B.Qu,B.Zk,B.Xk,B.Nl,B.SZ,B.Pb,B.Ns,B.Nw,B.XW,B.XA,B.TS,B.SW,B.PU,B.UN,B.W3,B.Pq,B.a_K,B.Ws,B.TJ,B.ZL,B.SL,B.UC,B.QI,B.XT,B.XM,B.ZN,B.Yc,B.Tz,B.Qx,B.Rm,B.ZB,B.OZ,B.XY,B.Ql,B.a__,B.VY,B.QN,B.QA,B.Oz,B.Of,B.Va,B.X0,B.Uz,B.P6,B.PL,B.XR,B.PP,B.S5,B.Tv],t.c)
B.a4O=s([B.k1,B.k2],A.aa("q<zM>"))
B.a7t=s(["Start levetiracetam as prophylaxis has been proven effective for late posttraumatic seizures.","Prophylaxis is not indicated to prevent this seizure as AEDs do not reduce the incidence of late posttraumatic seizures.","Continue phenytoin for 6 months because the patient is at high risk for posttraumatic epilepsy.","Initiate valproic acid immediately as it is the only AED proven to prevent late posttraumatic epilepsy."],t.s)
B.ahB=new A.O("A patient is 10 days post-severe TBI and experiences their first generalized tonic-clonic seizure. According to the Temkin trial and the 7-day rule, what is the most appropriate management regarding antiepileptic drug (AED) prophylaxis?",B.a7t,1,"The Temkin trial (1990) established that phenytoin and levetiracetam reduce early seizures but have no benefit in preventing seizures occurring more than 7 days post-injury.","medical-complications")
B.a54=s(["A mild TBI with a Loss of Consciousness (LOC) of 15 minutes.","A closed head injury with an Epidural Hematoma (EDH).","A penetrating head injury.","A patient with a GCS of 11 and a linear skull fracture."],t.s)
B.ahC=new A.O("Which of the following clinical scenarios represents the highest risk for developing late posttraumatic seizures (PTE)?",B.a54,2,"Penetrating injuries carry the highest incidence of late PTS, ranging from 33-50% .","medical-complications")
B.a8i=s(["Levetiracetam requires frequent drug level monitoring due to its narrow therapeutic index.","Phenytoin is a CYP450 inducer and has significant cognitive side effects.","Levetiracetam is more likely to impede neurological recovery than phenytoin.","Both medications are equally effective at preventing seizures after the first 7 days post-injury."],t.s)
B.afc=new A.O("When comparing phenytoin and levetiracetam for early posttraumatic seizure prophylaxis, which statement is accurate regarding their side effect profiles?",B.a8i,1,"Phenytoin is known to impair attention and processing speed while also interacting with many other medications via the cytochrome P450 system.","medical-complications")
B.a9m=s(["Dilation of the ventricles proportional to sulcal widening.","Presence of an Evans index of 0.25.","Presence of periventricular lucency and sulcal effacement.","Normal CSF flow void on MRI at the aqueduct."],t.s)
B.afW=new A.O("A patient with severe TBI shows ventricular dilation on CT. Which finding would most strongly suggest true Posttraumatic Hydrocephalus (PTH) rather than hydrocephalus ex vacuo?",B.a9m,2,"Periventricular lucency suggests transependymal CSF flow, and sulcal effacement indicates increased pressure rather than passive space-filling.","medical-complications")
B.aaq=s(["Urinary incontinence.","Dementia and cognitive slowing.","Gait disturbance.","Upper extremity spasticity."],t.s)
B.age=new A.O("According to the Hakim-Adams Syndrome (NPH triad), which clinical symptom is typically the first to appear and the most likely to respond to shunting?",B.aaq,2,"Gait disturbances, often described as 'magnetic' or shuffling, are the first symptom of the triad and show the best response to treatment.","medical-complications")
B.aa0=s(["Plain X-ray.","Triple-phase bone scan.","Serum alkaline phosphatase (SAP).","Ultrasound."],t.s)
B.ahG=new A.O("What is the most sensitive diagnostic test for the early detection of Heterotopic Ossification (HO) in a TBI patient, often turning positive 2-4 weeks before radiographic changes?",B.aa0,1,"The triple-phase bone scan is the gold standard for early detection because it identifies increased metabolic activity and blood flow before mineralization occurs.","medical-complications")
B.a8y=s(["6 months.","12 months.","18 months.","24 months."],t.s)
B.af3=new A.O("A 25-year-old with TBI-related Heterotopic Ossification (HO) at the hip is being considered for surgical excision. Based on Garland timing, how long should the surgical team wait post-injury to minimize the risk of recurrence?",B.a8y,2,"For TBI patients, the recommended Garland timing is 1.5 years to allow for complete bone maturation and metabolic stabilization.","medical-complications")
B.a4C=s(["Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) 5,000 U SC q8h starting immediately on admission.","Low Molecular Weight Heparin (LMWH), such as Enoxaparin, initiated 24-72 hours post-injury if CT is stable.","Aspirin 81 mg daily combined with sequential compression devices (SCDs).","Inferior Vena Cava (IVC) filter placement as the primary preventative measure."],t.s)
B.ah8=new A.O("Which of the following is the preferred pharmacologic strategy for Venous Thromboembolism (VTE) prophylaxis in TBI patients according to updated guidelines (2020-2024)?",B.a4C,1,"LMWH is associated with less VTE and higher survival compared to UFH in TBI patients, provided the follow-up CT shows no hemorrhage progression.","medical-complications")
B.a4y=s(["Cranial Nerve IV (Trochlear).","Cranial Nerve VI (Abducens).","Cranial Nerve III (Oculomotor).","Cranial Nerve II (Optic)."],t.s)
B.ag_=new A.O("A patient presents with a 'down and out' eye position, ptosis, and a dilated pupil that does not react to light. This clinical picture is most indicative of which cranial nerve injury?",B.a4y,2,"CN III palsy presents with the 'down and out' position and ptosis; pupil involvement suggests compression (e.g., from uncal herniation).","medical-complications")
B.aah=s(["Cranial Nerve VII (Facial).","Cranial Nerve VIII (Vestibulocochlear).","Cranial Nerve I (Olfactory).","Cranial Nerve IV (Trochlear)."],t.s)
B.agw=new A.O("Which cranial nerve is the ONLY one commonly injured in cases of mild TBI, often due to shearing at the cribriform plate?",B.aah,2,"The olfactory filaments are extremely delicate as they pass through the cribriform plate, making CN I vulnerable even in low-impact acceleration/deceleration injuries.","medical-complications")
B.aat=s(["Morphine.","Propranolol.","Gabapentin.","Bromocriptine."],t.s)
B.ahn=new A.O("In the management of Paroxysmal Sympathetic Hyperactivity (PSH), which medication is considered to have the best Cochrane evidence for recurrence prevention?",B.aat,1,"Propranolol, a non-selective beta-blocker, has the strongest evidence for reducing the frequency and severity of paroxysmal sympathetic surges.","medical-complications")
B.a8Y=s(["Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone (SIADH).","Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW).","Diabetes Insipidus (DI).","Psychogenic Polydipsia."],t.s)
B.agU=new A.O("A patient with TBI has a serum sodium of 128 mEq/L, high urine sodium, and high urine osmolality. Physical exam reveals dry mucous membranes and orthostatic hypotension. What is the most likely diagnosis?",B.a8Y,1,"The key differentiator between SIADH and CSW is volume status; CSW presents with hypovolemia (dehydration).","medical-complications")
B.a5P=s(["Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) deficiency.","Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) deficiency.","Growth Hormone (GH) deficiency.","Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) deficiency."],t.s)
B.ah3=new A.O("According to current screening protocols for post-traumatic hypopituitarism, which hormone deficiency is the MOST common finding 3-12 months after injury?",B.a5P,2,"Growth hormone deficiency is the most prevalent pituitary deficit observed in the chronic phase after TBI.","medical-complications")
B.a59=s(["Severe TBI with GCS 3-8.","Mild-to-moderate TBI with GCS 9-15.","Patients presenting more than 8 hours after injury.","Only in patients with penetrating TBI."],t.s)
B.agH=new A.O("The CRASH-3 trial provided evidence for the use of Tranexamic Acid (TXA) in TBI. In which patient population was a benefit in reducing head injury-related death demonstrated?",B.a59,1,"The benefit of TXA was specifically found in patients with mild-to-moderate TBI when administered within 3 hours of injury.","medical-complications")
B.a55=s(["Longitudinal fracture.","Transverse fracture.","Occipital condyle fracture.","Cribriform plate fracture."],t.s)
B.agA=new A.O("A patient suffers a temporal bone fracture. They present with sensorineural hearing loss and severe vertigo. Which type of temporal bone fracture is most likely?",B.a55,1,"Transverse fractures are more likely to involve the labyrinth and CN VIII, leading to sensorineural hearing loss and severe vertigo.","medical-complications")
B.a4S=s([B.ahB,B.ahC,B.afc,B.afW,B.age,B.ahG,B.af3,B.ah8,B.ag_,B.agw,B.ahn,B.agU,B.ah3,B.agH,B.agA],t.e)
B.a4V=s([18,15,10,12,15,18,15,12,12],t.n)
