B.a8P=s(["27.5%","33%","18%","40%"],t.s)
B.aft=new A.O("According to the 2024 systematic review and meta-analysis of 7,367 participants, what is the updated pooled prevalence of any pituitary axis dysfunction after traumatic brain injury?",B.a8P,1,"The most recent 2024 systematic review established this higher pooled estimate for post-TBI hypopituitarism.","neuroendocrine")
B.aa1=s(["ACTH deficiency","GH deficiency","TSH deficiency","ADH deficiency"],t.s)
B.afP=new A.O("Which pituitary hormone deficiency is considered the most common following a traumatic brain injury?",B.aa1,1,"Growth hormone deficiency is the most frequent deficit, with a pooled prevalence of approximately 18%.","neuroendocrine")
B.a4A=s(["Thyroid hormone can accelerate the metabolism of cortisol, precipitating an adrenal crisis.","Levothyroxine can falsely elevate cortisol levels, making diagnosis difficult.","Cortisol deficiency causes secondary hyperthyroidism that must be ruled out.","The hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis is more resilient than the thyroid axis."],t.s)
B.agJ=new A.O("When managing a TBI patient with multiple suspected endocrine deficits, why is it critical to check morning cortisol levels before initiating levothyroxine therapy?",B.a4A,0,"Starting thyroid replacement in the setting of untreated adrenal insufficiency can increase metabolic clearance of remaining cortisol, leading to a fatal crisis.","neuroendocrine")
B.a8d=s(["SIADH","Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW)","Central Diabetes Insipidus","Primary Polydipsia"],t.s)
B.aij=new A.O("A patient is 7 days post-TBI with a sodium level of 127 mEq/L. They are tachycardic, have dry mucous membranes, and show a negative fluid balance. What is the most likely diagnosis?",B.a8d,1,"The combination of hyponatremia and clinical dehydration (hypovolemia) is the hallmark differentiator for CSW.","neuroendocrine")
B.a5l=s(["15 mEq/L per 24 hours","10 mEq/L per 24 hours","5 mEq/L per 24 hours","20 mEq/L per 24 hours"],t.s)
B.afp=new A.O("What is the recommended maximum rate for correcting chronic hyponatremia to avoid Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome?",B.a5l,1,"Current board standards recommend limiting correction to no more than 10 mEq/L in a 24-hour period to ensure safety.","neuroendocrine")
B.a7D=s(["Massive polyuria due to hypothalamic shock.","Hyponatremia due to uncontrolled release of preformed ADH.","Permanent hypernatremia due to destruction of 80% of ADH neurons.","Sudden recovery of the thirst mechanism."],t.s)
B.ahT=new A.O("In the classic triphasic response of Central Diabetes Insipidus, what occurs during Phase 2 (typically days 5-10)?",B.a7D,1,"During Phase 2, dying neurons leak their stored ADH, causing an SIADH-like state that requires stopping DDAVP.","neuroendocrine")
B.a5C=s(["Serum osmolality","Fractional Excretion of Urate (FEurate)","Urine Sodium Concentration","Morning Cortisol Level"],t.s)
B.ai5=new A.O("Which diagnostic finding is the most reliable differentiator between SIADH and CSW AFTER hyponatremia has been corrected?",B.a5C,1,"FEurate remains elevated in CSW even after sodium correction but normalizes in SIADH, making it a valuable emerging tool.","neuroendocrine")
B.a53=s(["GH levels are always high in the acute phase of injury.","Early GH deficiencies are often transient and may resolve spontaneously.","IGF-1 is 100% sensitive in the first 6 months post-injury.","The medications used for stimulation testing are toxic during acute brain healing."],t.s)
B.ag5=new A.O("Why should Growth Hormone (GH) stimulation testing typically be deferred until 12 months post-TBI, even though it is the most common deficiency?",B.a53,1,"Since early pituitary dysfunction may recover, deferring to 12 months ensures that only permanent deficits are treated with long-term therapy.","neuroendocrine")
B.a6_=s(["The patient is euthyroid because the TSH is within the reference range.","This confirms central hypothyroidism because the TSH is 'inappropriately' normal.","This indicates Primary Hypothyroidism (Hashimoto's).","The labs likely reflect 'Euthyroid Sick Syndrome' which never requires treatment."],t.s)
B.afE=new A.O("A patient with suspected central hypothyroidism post-TBI has a lab report showing a normal TSH but a low Free T4. What is the correct interpretation of these results?",B.a6_,1,"The hallmark of secondary/central hypothyroidism is a low Free T4 without the expected compensatory rise in TSH.","neuroendocrine")
B.a3D=s(["It causes a global decrease in all pituitary hormones.","It leads to hyperprolactinemia due to the loss of dopaminergic inhibition.","It is the primary cause of central diabetes insipidus.","It causes a sudden surge in GH and ACTH due to shearing forces."],t.s)
B.ah5=new A.O("What is the clinical significance of the 'stalk effect' in a post-TBI patient?",B.a3D,1,"Dopamine from the hypothalamus normally inhibits prolactin; disruption of the stalk prevents this inhibition from reaching the pituitary.","neuroendocrine")
B.a8F=s(["Copeptin","IGF-1","B-type Natriuretic Peptide (BNP)","Prolactin"],t.s)
B.af2=new A.O("Which biomarker is considered an emerging, highly accurate tool for differentiating Central Diabetes Insipidus from primary polydipsia?",B.a8F,0,"Stimulated copeptin levels have shown 96.5% diagnostic accuracy in distinguishing between these two polyuric states.","neuroendocrine")
B.a8J=s(["IGF-1 screening; contraindicated in liver disease.","Insulin Tolerance Test (ITT); contraindicated in seizure disorders and CAD.","Macimorelin Test; contraindicated in patients with obesity.","Glucagon stimulation; contraindicated in Type 1 Diabetes."],t.s)
B.agI=new A.O("What is the gold standard confirmatory test for Growth Hormone Deficiency, and what is its primary contraindication?",B.a8J,1,"ITT is the gold standard but is risky for TBI patients with a history of seizures or heart disease.","neuroendocrine")
B.a88=s(["Only those with severe TBI and symptoms of fatigue.","All patients with moderate-to-severe TBI, regardless of symptoms.","Only patients who have sustained a basilar skull fracture.","Patients with mild TBI who are returning to work immediately."],t.s)
B.ah6=new A.O("Consensus guidelines from the Endocrine Society and British Neurotrauma Group recommend screening for hypopituitarism in which population?",B.a88,1,"Because symptoms of hypopituitarism overlap significantly with general TBI recovery, screening must be universal for these severities.","neuroendocrine")
B.a4E=s(["Replacement increases the risk of post-traumatic seizures.","Replacement does not increase aggression or agitation in TBI patients.","Replacement prevents the development of heterotopic ossification.","Replacement reduces the risk of deep vein thrombosis."],t.s)
B.ahy=new A.O("Research into testosterone replacement after TBI has addressed which common clinical concern regarding its safety?",B.a4E,1,"Studies actually showed an inverse correlation between agitation and testosterone, with no increase in aggressive behavior during replacement.","neuroendocrine")
B.a63=s(["Levothyroxine 100 mcg daily","Hydrocortisone 15-25 mg/day in divided doses","Dexamethasone 4 mg IV every 6 hours","Fludrocortisone 0.1 mg daily"],t.s)
B.ag8=new A.O("A patient is diagnosed with adrenal insufficiency following a stimulation test. What is the standard recommended maintenance treatment?",B.a63,1,"Hydrocortisone is the standard replacement, typically given as 10 mg in the morning and 5 mg in the evening.","neuroendocrine")
B.a5t=s([B.aft,B.afP,B.agJ,B.aij,B.afp,B.ahT,B.ai5,B.ag5,B.afE,B.ah5,B.af2,B.agI,B.ah6,B.ahy,B.ag8],t.e)
B.ZQ=new A.c("What is the only effective strategy for managing primary brain injury?","Prevention.")
B.MO=new A.c("Which type of force is identified as the most damaging in TBI due to its ability to shear axons?","Rotational or angular acceleration.")
B.Yt=new A.c("Which specific TBI mechanism is most likely to produce focal injuries rather than diffuse axonal injury?","Translational (linear) acceleration.")
B.R9=new A.c("What is the estimated seizure risk associated with penetrating brain injuries?","33%-50%.")
B.O5=new A.c("Term: Coup contusion","Definition: A brain contusion located directly beneath the point of impact.")
B.PS=new A.c("Term: Contrecoup contusion","Definition: A contusion occurring on the side opposite the point of impact due to brain rebounding.")
B.MX=new A.c("Why are the inferior frontal lobes and anterior temporal tips the most common locations for contusions?","The rough bony surfaces of the anterior and middle cranial fossae.")
B.Zf=new A.c("What is the typical clinical presentation of orbitofrontal contusions?","Personality changes, disinhibition, and impaired social judgment.")
B.Pn=new A.c("Temporal tip contusions are primarily associated with deficits in _____.","Memory and emotional regulation.")
B.a_0=new A.c("What is the 'blossoming' window for brain contusions requiring serial CT monitoring?","24-72 hours.")
B.VA=new A.c("What is the most common vascular source of an epidural hematoma (EDH)?","Middle meningeal artery.")
B.Z0=new A.c("What is the characteristic CT appearance of an epidural hematoma?","Biconvex or lens-shaped hyperdensity.")
B.Pz=new A.c("How do epidural hematomas relate to cranial suture lines on imaging?","They do not cross suture lines.")
B.WY=new A.c("Which focal hemorrhage type is characterized by a crescent shape that crosses suture lines but not the midline falx?","Subdural hematoma (SDH).")
B.N4=new A.c("What is the primary vascular source of a subdural hematoma?","Torn bridging veins.")
B.VW=new A.c("At what time interval does a subdural hematoma appear isodense on a CT scan?","3 days to 3 weeks (Subacute phase).")
B.Tq=new A.c("What secondary complications are associated with traumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH)?","Vasospasm and communicating hydrocephalus.")
B.Y4=new A.c("What is the leading cause of morbidity and prolonged unconsciousness in TBI?","Diffuse Axonal Injury (DAI).")
B.ST=new A.c("Axonal injury in DAI is primarily a result of secondary axotomy caused by cytoskeletal disruption and _____.","Calcium-mediated proteolysis.")
B.St=new A.c("Why does myelin debris actively inhibit remyelination after TBI?","It blocks oligodendrocyte progenitor cell (OPC) differentiation.")
B.Xb=new A.c("Which receptor mediates the suppression of axon regeneration by myelin-associated inhibitors like Nogo-A?","NgR1 receptor.")
B.ML=new A.c("Term: Retraction balls","Definition: Swollen proximal stumps of disconnected axons that serve as the pathognomonic hallmark of DAI.")
B.a_H=new A.c("Which immunohistochemical stain is used to visualize retraction balls in DAI?","Beta-amyloid precursor protein (beta-APP).")
B.V8=new A.c("What characterizes Grade 2 of the Adams DAI Grading System?","Axonal injury in the white matter and the corpus callosum.")
B.Rl=new A.c("In the Adams DAI Grading System, Grade 3 involves injury to the _____.","Dorsolateral midbrain and upper brainstem.")
B.Sb=new A.c("Which specific part of the corpus callosum is most frequently injured in DAI?","Posterior body and splenium.")
B.V_=new A.c("Injury to which structure in DAI results in severe memory impairment?","Fornix.")
B.R5=new A.c("Which MRI sequence is 3-6 times more sensitive than conventional GRE for detecting hemorrhagic DAI?","Susceptibility Weighted Imaging (SWI).")
B.WZ=new A.c("What is the imaging biomarker of choice for identifying subtle DAI when conventional MRI is normal?","Diffusion Tensor Imaging (DTI) showing decreased fractional anisotropy.")
B.Sm=new A.c("What is the primary difference between primary and secondary brain injury in terms of clinical management?","Secondary injury is potentially preventable and treatable.")
B.Xl=new A.c("In the excitotoxicity cascade, massive calcium influx activates which enzymes that lead to cellular destruction?","Calpains, lipases, and endonucleases.")
B.XO=new A.c("According to the Giza & Hovda model, what causes the 'hyperglycolysis' phase after concussion?","Na+/K+ ATPase pumps working overtime to restore ionic balance.")
B.Od=new A.c("What is the duration of the physiological 'vulnerability window' following a concussion?","3-5 days.")
B.OG=new A.c("What catastrophic event can occur if a second impact is sustained during the post-concussion metabolic vulnerability window?","Second Impact Syndrome (catastrophic cerebral edema).")
B.a_D=new A.c("How long does metabolic recovery typically take in the adult brain following a concussion?","7-10 days.")
B.ME=new A.c("Which type of cerebral edema is characterized by Na+/K+ ATPase failure and intracellular swelling?","Cytotoxic edema.")
B.Vh=new A.c("Why are steroids contraindicated in the management of severe TBI?","They do not treat cytotoxic edema and were shown to increase mortality in the CRASH trial.")
B.OW=new A.c("Term: Ferroptosis","Definition: An iron-dependent form of regulated cell death driven by lipid peroxidation.")
B.Pc=new A.c("Which enzyme is the key inhibitor of ferroptosis by preventing lipid ROS accumulation?","Glutathione peroxidase 4 (GPX4).")
B.a_I=new A.c("During which time frame post-TBI does the M2 (anti-inflammatory) microglial phenotype typically peak?","Days 3-5.")
B.Ty=new A.c("At what point post-injury does the M1 (pro-inflammatory) microglial phenotype begin to dominate?","Day 7.")
B.Qi=new A.c("What is the biphasic timeline for blood-brain barrier (BBB) disruption after TBI?","Initial disruption at 3-6 hours and a second wave at 1-3 days.")
B.Nb=new A.c("What percentage of late TBI survivors (>1 year) demonstrate persistent, widespread BBB disruption?","47%.")
B.N9=new A.c("What is the primary function of the glymphatic system?","Waste clearance from the brain parenchyma mediated by AQP4 channels on astrocytes.")
B.T7=new A.c("How much does glymphatic clearance increase during sleep compared to wakefulness?","60%.")
B.YK=new A.c("Where does tau protein typically deposit in Chronic Traumatic Encephalopathy (CTE)?","Sulcal depths in a perivascular distribution.")
B.QD=new A.c("Term: Cortical spreading depolarization (CSD)","Definition: Waves of near-complete neuronal depolarization propagating across the cortex at 2-5 mm/min.")
B.O2=new A.c("How does TBI affect the gut-brain axis within hours of injury?","It increases intestinal permeability ('leaky gut') and causes gut dysbiosis.")
B.UG=new A.c("What were the results of Phase III clinical trials (ProTECT III/SyNAPSe) regarding progesterone in TBI?","They showed no benefit over placebo.")
B.OD=new A.c("Severe TBI promotes mitochondrial _____, which fragments mitochondria and leads to neurodegeneration.","Fission (via Drp1).")
B.Xi=new A.c("What is the normal MAP range over which cerebral autoregulation maintains constant blood flow?","50-150 mmHg.")
B.MZ=new A.c("According to the Monro-Kellie Doctrine, what are the three primary components of the rigid skull container?","Brain (~80%), blood (~10%), and CSF (~10%).")
B.O9=new A.c("What is the BTF treatment threshold for intracranial pressure (ICP)?",">22 mmHg.")
B.Yf=new A.c("What is the formula for calculating Cerebral Perfusion Pressure (CPP)?","CPP = MAP - ICP.")
B.Rf=new A.c("What is the recommended target range for CPP in the management of severe TBI?","60-70 mmHg.")
B.ZH=new A.c("In the 'CRASH HIT' mnemonic for secondary insults, what does the 'H' in 'HIT' represent?","Hypotension (SBP < 90 mmHg).")
B.Zc=new A.c("A single episode of systolic blood pressure (SBP) less than _____ mmHg doubles mortality in TBI.","90.")
B.Yd=new A.c("How much does metabolic demand increase for each degree Celsius above 37 degrees C?","10%-13%.")
B.a_h=new A.c("By what factor do seizures increase the metabolic demand of the brain?","3-5 times.")
