B.UZ=new A.c("Two-thirds of severe TBI mortalities show structural abnormalities in which specific brain region?","The hypothalamic-pituitary region.")
B.TK=new A.c("Which part of the pituitary gland receives an indirect blood supply via portal vessels, making it highly vulnerable to ischemia?","The anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis).")
B.UX=new A.c("The posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis) primarily stores and releases which two hormones?","ADH (vasopressin) and oxytocin.")
B.RU=new A.c("What is the most common pituitary hormone deficiency observed after TBI?","Growth Hormone (GH) deficiency (18% prevalence).")
B.NY=new A.c("What is the second most common pituitary axis affected by TBI?","The gonadal axis (LH/FSH) with a 16% prevalence.")
B.OI=new A.c("What is the pooled prevalence of ACTH deficiency (adrenal axis) post-TBI?","10%")
B.Rx=new A.c("What is the pooled prevalence of TSH deficiency (thyroid axis) post-TBI?","6%")
B.OM=new A.c("According to consensus guidelines, at what two time points post-injury should TBI patients be screened for hypopituitarism?","3 months and 12 months post-injury.")
B.VM=new A.c("Which hormonal test must always be checked first in a post-TBI screening panel to rule out the most dangerous deficiency?","Morning cortisol.")
B.Ug=new A.c("Why is Growth Hormone (GH) stimulation testing typically deferred until 12 months post-injury?","Early GH deficiencies are often transient and may resolve spontaneously within the first year.")
B.Ou=new A.c("DOD 2022 guidance recommends neuroendocrine screening for mild TBI (concussion) under what condition?","When symptoms persist after the injury.")
B.TY=new A.c("Why is IGF-1 alone considered an unreliable screening tool for Growth Hormone deficiency in adults?","IGF-1 levels can be falsely normal in up to 30% of GH-deficient adults.")
B.Th=new A.c('What is the "gold standard" test for confirming Growth Hormone deficiency, despite its risks?',"The Insulin Tolerance Test (ITT).")
B.Xq=new A.c("List two absolute contraindications for the Insulin Tolerance Test (ITT).","Seizure disorders and coronary artery disease.")
B.RL=new A.c("Which FDA-approved oral GH stimulation test, noted for its high sensitivity and specificity, uses a GH cutoff of 5.1 ng/mL?","Macimorelin (Macrilen).")
B.Sn=new A.c("Untreated GH deficiency in TBI patients primarily impacts which clinical domains?","Body composition, cognition (executive function/memory), and quality of life.")
B.Rk=new A.c("What is the most common cause of hyponatremia after TBI?","Syndrome of Inappropriate ADH Secretion (SIADH).")
B.Yu=new A.c("Describe the volume status of a patient with SIADH.","Euvolemic.")
B.a_y=new A.c("What are the typical urine findings in SIADH regarding osmolality and sodium?","High urine osmolality (>100 mOsm/kg) and high urine sodium (>40 mEq/L).")
B.Ux=new A.c("What is the first-line treatment for hyponatremia caused by SIADH?","Fluid restriction (1.0-1.2 L/day).")
B.O_=new A.c("Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW) is distinguished from SIADH primarily by which clinical feature?","Volume status (CSW is hypovolemic; SIADH is euvolemic).")
B.YF=new A.c("What is the primary treatment for Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW)?","Volume replacement with normal saline or hypertonic saline.")
B.YI=new A.c("How does the Fractional Excretion of Urate (FEurate) behave in SIADH after the hyponatremia is corrected?","It normalizes.")
B.Vx=new A.c("How does the Fractional Excretion of Urate (FEurate) behave in Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW) after the hyponatremia is corrected?","It remains elevated (>11%).")
B.W9=new A.c("To avoid Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome, what is the maximum recommended rate of sodium correction over 24 hours?","10 mEq/L.")
B.V9=new A.c('What life-threatening condition, characterized by quadriparesis and "locked-in" syndrome, results from the overcorrection of chronic hyponatremia?',"Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome (ODS).")
