B.Ss=new A.c("What is the normal cortisol response threshold 30 or 60 minutes after a 250 mcg Cosyntropin stimulation test?",">=18 mcg/dL")
B.YJ=new A.c("What is the standard daily replacement regimen for hydrocortisone in adrenal insufficiency?","15-25 mg/day divided into AM and PM doses.")
B.Wp=new A.c("Mnemonic: Why is it critical to check cortisol before starting thyroid replacement?","Starting levothyroxine in a cortisol-deficient patient can precipitate a fatal adrenal crisis.")
B.TC=new A.c("Why is checking only TSH insufficient to screen for hypothyroidism in TBI patients?","In central hypothyroidism, TSH may be normal or low; the diagnosis requires a low Free T4.")
B.a_R=new A.c('What is the "stalk effect" and its impact on prolactin levels?',"Injury to the pituitary stalk disrupts dopaminergic inhibition, causing an elevation in prolactin.")
B.QF=new A.c("In a post-TBI patient, a prolactin level exceeding _____ should trigger an investigation for a prolactinoma.","200 ng/mL")
B.Ue=new A.c("Which hormonal deficiency is most likely to cause persistent fatigue and decreased muscle mass recovery during rehabilitation?","Hypogonadism (testosterone deficiency).")
B.R8=new A.c("True or False: Testosterone replacement in hypogonadal TBI patients has been shown to increase agitation and aggression.","False")
B.PN=new A.c("What is the most common permanent neuroendocrine deficit following traumatic brain injury?","Growth Hormone (GH) deficiency.")
B.SH=new A.c("A patient with low sodium, low serum osmolality, tachycardia, and a high BUN/Cr ratio most likely has which disorder?","Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW).")
B.Ry=new A.c("A patient with low sodium, low serum osmolality, and stable weight/moist mucous membranes most likely has which disorder?","SIADH.")
B.X5=new A.c("Which medication is used to treat the polyuria associated with Central Diabetes Insipidus?","Desmopressin (DDAVP).")
B.Yq=new A.c("What is the significance of a Copeptin level >4.9 pmol/L following stimulation?","It distinguishes Central DI from primary polydipsia with high accuracy.")
B.Py=new A.c("At what time point post-TBI is the prevalence of hypopituitarism at its lowest (26%)?","6 to 12 months post-injury.")
B.Zo=new A.c("Which pituitary lobe has a direct arterial supply and stores hormones produced in the hypothalamus?","The posterior pituitary.")
B.QR=new A.c("During the Triphasic Response of DI, when does the SIADH-like Phase 2 usually occur?","Days 5 to 10 post-injury.")
B.P_=new A.c("What laboratory finding regarding TSH and T4 confirms central hypothyroidism?","A low Free T4 with an inappropriately normal or low TSH.")
B.WU=new A.c("How should hydrocortisone dosing be adjusted during periods of acute illness or surgery in a deficient patient?","The maintenance dose should be doubled or tripled (stress dosing).")
B.YV=new A.c("Untreated neuroendocrine dysfunction in the TBI population is independently associated with which long-term outcome?","Delayed functional recovery and poor quality of life.")
B.RV=new A.c("Which specific hormone deficiency is most likely to cause refractory hypotension and hypoglycemia?","ACTH deficiency.")
B.a_L=new A.c("Is GH deficiency more common in moderate-severe TBI or mild TBI?","It is more common as severity increases, but it can still occur in mild TBI.")
B.RF=new A.c("What is the clinical management for a patient in Phase 1 of the Triphasic Response of DI?","DDAVP administration and free water access/replacement.")
B.a_e=new A.c("A patient 6 months post-TBI has fatigue and omental weight gain; IGF-1 is low-normal. What is the next diagnostic step?","A Growth Hormone stimulation test (e.g., Glucagon or Macimorelin).")
B.Pw=new A.c("What change in fluid balance and sodium is a clinical clue for the onset of Phase 2 in the Triphasic Response?","Positive fluid balance and a falling serum sodium level.")
B.YQ=new A.c("What is the typical urine output threshold used to diagnose Diabetes Insipidus?",">3 L/day")
B.P1=new A.c("Mnemonic: 'SIADH Sits, CSW _____'?","Shrinks (referring to volume status).")
B.W8=new A.c("Which axis deficiency is associated with amenorrhea and osteoporosis in females?","The gonadal axis (LH/FSH).")
B.a_q=new A.c("What is the mechanism of action for fludrocortisone in the treatment of Cerebral Salt Wasting?","It promotes renal sodium reabsorption to counteract salt wasting.")
B.TR=new A.c("Which hormone deficiency post-TBI is most associated with cold intolerance and cognitive slowing?","TSH deficiency (Central Hypothyroidism).")
B.Np=new A.c("According to the 2024 meta-analysis, what percentage of patients still have pituitary dysfunction more than 12 months after injury?","32%")
B.Tj=new A.c("Which test should be performed if a morning cortisol level is between 3 and 18 mcg/dL?","Cosyntropin (ACTH) stimulation test.")
B.N_=new A.c("What is the term for the clinical condition resulting from the rapid correction of hyponatremia?","Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome.")
B.PM=new A.c("Why might a patient with TBI have an elevated hematocrit and elevated BUN/Cr ratio in the setting of hyponatremia?","Hemoconcentration due to volume depletion in Cerebral Salt Wasting (CSW).")
B.MP=new A.c("Which sodium disorder involves water retention leading to dilutional hyponatremia?","SIADH.")
B.Tt=new A.c("True or False: Prolactin is the only anterior pituitary hormone that typically increases rather than decreases after stalk injury.","True")
B.TG=new A.c("What is the primary management for Phase 2 of the Triphasic DI response?","Stopping DDAVP and initiating fluid restriction.")
B.Z7=new A.c("Which diagnostic test differentiates central DI from primary polydipsia by measuring a precursor to ADH?","Stimulated Copeptin.")
B.R2=new A.c("Post-TBI hypopituitarism prevalence is highest during which time period?","The first 3 months (40%).")
B.Zm=new A.c("Is the hypophyseal portal system more likely to be damaged in a front-to-back or side-to-side acceleration/deceleration injury?","Shearing of the stalk can occur in any acceleration/deceleration injury, but portal veins are especially vulnerable to disruption.")
B.RM=new A.c("In central hypothyroidism, why does TSH fail to rise despite low T4 levels?","The pituitary gland is unable to secrete TSH in response to low thyroid hormone levels.")
B.Wa=new A.c("What effect does GH replacement have on cardiovascular risk factors in deficient TBI patients?","It can improve abnormal lipid metabolism and reduce insulin resistance.")
B.RH=new A.c("What is the incidence of the Triphasic Response among all TBI patients?","1.1%")
B.iD=s([B.Ve,B.Yl,B.Pg,B.Wy,B.UZ,B.TK,B.UX,B.RU,B.NY,B.OI,B.Rx,B.OM,B.VM,B.Ug,B.Ou,B.TY,B.Th,B.Xq,B.RL,B.Sn,B.Rk,B.Yu,B.a_y,B.Ux,B.O_,B.YF,B.YI,B.Vx,B.W9,B.V9,B.Rd,B.Tc,B.VB,B.OU,B.Se,B.Pt,B.TF,B.Sf,B.Ss,B.YJ,B.Wp,B.TC,B.a_R,B.QF,B.Ue,B.R8,B.PN,B.SH,B.Ry,B.X5,B.Yq,B.Py,B.Zo,B.QR,B.P_,B.WU,B.YV,B.RV,B.a_L,B.RF,B.a_e,B.Pw,B.YQ,B.P1,B.W8,B.a_q,B.TR,B.Np,B.Tj,B.N_,B.PM,B.MP,B.Tt,B.TG,B.Z7,B.R2,B.Zm,B.RM,B.Wa,B.RH],t.c)
B.a8Z=s(["ICP should be treated when >22 mmHg","CPP should be maintained at 60-70 mmHg","Steroids are NOT recommended for TBI","Prophylactic hypothermia improves outcomes"],t.s)
B.agr=new A.O("What is the ONLY Level I recommendation in the BTF 4th Edition Guidelines?",B.a8Z,2,"The CRASH trial (2004, >10,000 patients) showed methylprednisolone INCREASED 2-week mortality (RR 1.18). Steroids are contraindicated in TBI \u2014 this is the ONLY Level I recommendation in the entire BTF 4th edition.","tbi-fundamentals")
B.a5d=s([">15 mmHg",">20 mmHg",">22 mmHg",">25 mmHg"],t.s)
B.afg=new A.O("What is the ICP treatment threshold per the BTF 4th Edition (2016)?",B.a5d,2,'The BTF 4th Edition changed the ICP treatment threshold from 20 to 22 mmHg. "22 is the new 20." Normal adult ICP is 5-15 mmHg (supine).',"tbi-fundamentals")
B.a93=s(["LOC of 15 minutes","PTA of 18 hours","GCS of 14","PTA of 36 hours"],t.s)
B.ai8=new A.O("According to the ACRM definition, which of the following EXCEEDS criteria for mild TBI?",B.a93,3,"Mild TBI criteria: LOC <30 min, PTA <24 hrs, initial GCS \u226513. PTA of 36 hours exceeds the 24-hour limit, making this at least a moderate TBI.","tbi-fundamentals")
B.a9f=s(["Motor vehicle crashes","Falls","Assault","Sports injuries"],t.s)
B.ahS=new A.O("What is the leading cause of TBI-related death in adults \u226575 years?",B.a9f,1,"Falls are the leading cause of TBI in the very young (0-4) and elderly (\u226575). Adults \u226575 have the highest mortality rate from TBI, primarily from falls.","tbi-fundamentals")
B.a7L=s(["Mannitol 20%","Hypertonic saline 3%","Furosemide","Dexamethasone"],t.s)
B.afR=new A.O("A hypotensive patient with elevated ICP needs osmolar therapy. Which agent is preferred?",B.a7L,1,"Mannitol causes osmotic diuresis \u2192 volume depletion \u2192 worsening hypotension. Hypertonic saline does NOT cause diuresis and can actually expand intravascular volume. Dexamethasone (steroid) is contraindicated in TBI.","tbi-fundamentals")
B.a6p=s(["Occipital lobes and cerebellum","Inferior frontal and anterior temporal lobes","Parietal lobes bilaterally","Thalamus and basal ganglia"],t.s)
B.ai7=new A.O("Which brain regions are MOST susceptible to contusions due to the rough inner skull surface?",B.a6p,1,"The rough bony ridges of the anterior and middle cranial fossae make the orbitofrontal and anterior temporal regions most vulnerable to contusions (coup-contrecoup).","pathophysiology")
B.a5n=s(["Subdural hematoma","Epidural hematoma","Subarachnoid hemorrhage","Intraparenchymal hemorrhage"],t.s)
B.ahp=new A.O("A CT shows a biconvex (lens-shaped) hyperdense extra-axial collection. What is the most likely diagnosis?",B.a5n,1,"Epidural hematomas are biconvex/lenticular in shape, typically from rupture of the middle meningeal artery. They are bounded by suture lines. SDH appears crescent-shaped and crosses sutures.","pathophysiology")
B.a5B=s(["Grade 1","Grade 2","Grade 3","Grade 4"],t.s)
B.afb=new A.O("What is the Adams grading of DAI when hemorrhagic lesions are found in the corpus callosum?",B.a5B,1,"Adams DAI grading: Grade 1 = white matter of cerebral hemispheres, Grade 2 = corpus callosum involvement, Grade 3 = brainstem (dorsolateral) involvement. Higher grade = worse prognosis.","pathophysiology")
B.a6M=s(["Non-contrast CT","T1-weighted MRI","Susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI)","Plain skull radiograph"],t.s)
B.ag4=new A.O("Which imaging modality is MOST sensitive for detecting diffuse axonal injury?",B.a6M,2,"SWI is 3-6x more sensitive than conventional gradient-recalled echo (GRE) for detecting microhemorrhages associated with DAI. Standard CT misses most DAI. DTI can detect axonal disruption even without hemorrhage.","pathophysiology")
B.a5h=s(["GABA","Dopamine","Glutamate","Serotonin"],t.s)
B.ai3=new A.O("Which neurotransmitter is primarily responsible for the excitotoxic cascade following TBI?",B.a5h,2,"Within minutes of TBI, excessive glutamate release triggers NMDA receptor activation \u2192 unregulated calcium influx \u2192 activation of Ca\xb2\u207a-dependent proteases \u2192 mitochondrial injury \u2192 apoptosis. This excitotoxic cascade is the primary driver of secondary injury.","pathophysiology")
B.a96=s(["7","8","9","10"],t.s)
B.ai2=new A.O("A patient opens eyes to pain, makes incomprehensible sounds, and has flexion withdrawal. What is their GCS?",B.a96,1,"Eye opening to pain = 2, Incomprehensible sounds = 2, Flexion withdrawal = 4. Total GCS = 2+2+4 = 8. This patient is at the threshold for coma (GCS \u22648).","classification-severity")
B.a5g=s(["Eye opening","Verbal response","Motor response","All three equally"],t.s)
B.af4=new A.O("Which component of the GCS is the strongest predictor of outcome?",B.a5g,2,"The motor component of the GCS is the strongest single predictor of outcome after TBI. This is why the FOUR Score, which does not rely on verbal response, remains valid in intubated patients.","classification-severity")
B.a9l=s(["Localized response","Confused-agitated","Confused-inappropriate","Automatic-appropriate"],t.s)
B.ahl=new A.O("A patient at Rancho Level IV would be described as:",B.a9l,1,"Rancho IV = Confused and Agitated. Key features: heightened state of activity, bizarre/non-purposeful behavior, no short-term memory, unable to cooperate with treatment. Management: low-stimulation environment, 1:1 supervision, safety measures.","classification-severity")
B.a77=s(["Initial GCS score","Duration of loss of consciousness","Duration of posttraumatic amnesia","CT findings on admission"],t.s)
B.ahq=new A.O("Which of the following is the strongest single predictor of functional outcome after TBI?",B.a77,2,"PTA duration is consistently the strongest single predictor of functional recovery after TBI. Longer PTA = poorer outcomes. PTA >1 week suggests severe injury.","classification-severity")
B.a5y=s(["5-10%","15-20%","30-40%","50-60%"],t.s)
B.agX=new A.O("What is the misdiagnosis rate for disorders of consciousness (VS vs MCS)?",B.a5y,2,"Studies consistently show a 30-40% misdiagnosis rate for disorders of consciousness, primarily VS being misdiagnosed in patients who are actually in MCS. The CRS-R helps reduce this rate through standardized behavioral assessment.","classification-severity")
B.aam=s(["Methylprednisolone 30 mg/kg IV","Tranexamic acid 1g IV bolus + 1g over 8h","Erythropoietin 40,000 IU SC","Progesterone IV infusion"],t.s)
B.agB=new A.O("A patient with mild-moderate TBI (GCS 12) presents 2 hours after injury. Which pharmacologic intervention has Level 1 evidence for reducing head injury death?",B.aam,1,"CRASH-3 (Lancet 2019): TXA 1g bolus + 1g over 8h reduces head injury death in GCS 9-15 when given within 3 hours (RR 0.78). Steroids INCREASE mortality (CRASH trial). EPO and progesterone both showed NO benefit in Phase III trials.","acute-management")
B.aa7=s(["GFAP <100 pg/mL, UCH-L1 <500 pg/mL","GFAP <22 pg/mL, UCH-L1 <327 pg/mL","GFAP <50 ng/mL, UCH-L1 <100 ng/mL","GFAP <10 pg/mL, UCH-L1 <50 pg/mL"],t.s)
B.ahx=new A.O("What are the FDA-cleared cutoff values for the Banyan Brain Trauma Indicator (GFAP and UCH-L1) used to rule out CT-positive findings in mild TBI?",B.aa7,1,"The Banyan BTI (FDA-cleared 2018, validated by ALERT-TBI; Bazarian et al., Lancet Neurol 2018) uses cutoffs of GFAP <22 pg/mL AND UCH-L1 <327 pg/mL \u2014 both must be below threshold for a negative result. Sensitivity 97.6%, NPV 99.6% for CT-positive intracranial lesions in adults with GCS 13-15 within 12 hours of injury. The Abbott i-STAT TBI Plasma cartridge (FDA-cleared 2021) and i-STAT TBI Whole Blood (2023) deliver bedside results in ~15 minutes using the same cutoffs.","acute-management")
B.a6T=s(["Significantly reduced mortality","Was not superior; both groups had similar outcomes","Increased mortality due to monitor complications","Improved functional outcomes at 12 months"],t.s)
B.afS=new A.O("The BEST-TRIP trial demonstrated that ICP monitoring-guided care compared to imaging/clinical exam-guided care:",B.a6T,1,"BEST-TRIP (Chesnut, NEJM 2012): Mortality 39% vs 41% (P=0.60) \u2014 no difference. The imaging group received MORE empiric treatment (4.8 vs 3.4 days). This does NOT invalidate ICP monitoring \u2014 it tested treatment protocols, not monitoring utility. BTF still recommends monitoring.","acute-management")
B.aa8=s(["Tier 1","Tier 2","Tier 3","Not included"],t.s)
B.agx=new A.O("In the SIBICC algorithm, at which tier is decompressive craniectomy classified?",B.aa8,2,"SIBICC classifies DC as a Tier 3 (last resort, highest risk) intervention. Tier 1 = favorable side-effect profile (HOB elevation, sedation, normothermia, EVD, osmotherapy). Tier 2 = moderate risk (hyperventilation, NMBAs, MAP challenge). Tier 3 = barbiturate coma, therapeutic hypothermia, and DC.","acute-management")
B.a3A=s(["Hemorrhagic shock causing dilutional coagulopathy","DIC from systemic infection","Massive tissue factor release from injured brain activating extrinsic cascade","Vitamin K deficiency from poor nutrition"],t.s)
B.agn=new A.O("Which of the following is the primary mechanism of acute coagulopathy in TBI?",B.a3A,2,"TBI coagulopathy is brain-derived: injured brain releases massive tissue factor (brain has highest TF concentration of any organ), activating the extrinsic coagulation cascade \u2192 consumptive coagulopathy with fibrinogen nadir at 3-6 hours. Occurs in up to 60% of severe TBI. TEG/ROTEM is more sensitive than standard labs.","acute-management")
B.a4Q=s(["Progesterone \u2014 ProTECT III (negative)","EPO \u2014 EPO-TBI trial (negative)","TXA \u2014 CRASH-3 (positive in GCS 9-15)","Hypothermia \u2014 POLAR trial (negative)"],t.s)
B.afJ=new A.O("Which of the following neuroprotective agents has been proven INEFFECTIVE in TBI by Phase III trials? (Select the INCORRECT pairing)",B.a4Q,2,"TXA (CRASH-3) showed BENEFIT in GCS 9-15 patients within 3 hours. All others are confirmed negative: ProTECT III and SyNAPSe (progesterone), EPO-TBI (erythropoietin), POLAR and Eurotherm (hypothermia), and CRASH (steroids \u2014 increased mortality).","acute-management")
B.a62=s(["Succinylcholine \u2014 fastest onset","Cisatracurium \u2014 Hofmann elimination, no histamine release","Vecuronium \u2014 longest duration","Atracurium \u2014 cheapest option"],t.s)
B.afL=new A.O("What is the preferred neuromuscular blocking agent for ICP management and why?",B.a62,1,"Cisatracurium is preferred: no histamine release (unlike atracurium), no effect on ICP/CPP, and organ-independent metabolism (Hofmann elimination) \u2014 ideal for renal/hepatic dysfunction. Succinylcholine can elevate ICP and cause hyperkalemia. NMBAs are a SIBICC Tier 2 intervention.","acute-management")
B.a9U=s(["Improved neurological outcomes and reduced mortality","Decreased ICP but was associated with MORE unfavorable outcomes","Had no effect on ICP or outcomes","Increased mortality compared to medical management"],t.s)
B.ahd=new A.O("The DECRA trial showed that early bifrontal decompressive craniectomy for diffuse TBI:",B.a9U,1,"DECRA (Cooper, NEJM 2011): Early bifrontal DC for diffuse TBI decreased ICP effectively but was associated with more unfavorable outcomes (increased vegetative state). The RESCUEicp trial later showed DC reduced mortality but increased severe disability.","acute-management")
B.a6l=s(["40-50 mmHg","50-60 mmHg","60-70 mmHg","70-80 mmHg"],t.s)
B.ag2=new A.O("What is the target CPP range recommended by the BTF 4th Edition?",B.a6l,2,"CPP = MAP - ICP. Target: 60-70 mmHg. CPP <50 is associated with poor outcomes. The BTF specifically warns against pushing CPP >70 with vasopressors due to ARDS risk.","acute-management")
B.a5z=s(["Within 24 hours","By day 3","By day 5-7","After ICP normalizes"],t.s)
B.ah2=new A.O("When should feeding be initiated in severe TBI per BTF 4th Edition?",B.a5z,2,"BTF 4th Ed recommends feeding by day 5-7 to decrease mortality. TBI patients are hypermetabolic (140% caloric expenditure). Protein needs: 1.5-2 g/kg/day. Transgastric jejunal feeding reduces aspiration risk.","acute-management")
B.a5H=s(["Eye opening to command","Functional object use OR reliable communication","Consistent localization to pain","Spontaneous eye tracking"],t.s)
B.ai_=new A.O("Emergence from MCS requires demonstration of:",B.a5H,1,"Emergence from MCS requires reliable and consistent demonstration of EITHER: (1) functional object use, OR (2) interactive communication. Visual pursuit alone indicates MCS, not emergence.","disorders-of-consciousness")
B.a9d=s(["No benefit for disorders of consciousness","Faster DRS improvement during treatment, with convergence after washout","Sustained improvement that persisted after medication was stopped","Benefit only in vegetative state, not MCS"],t.s)
B.afk=new A.O("The Giacino et al. NEJM 2012 amantadine trial showed:",B.a9d,1,"Giacino trial: n=184, VS/MCS at 4-16 weeks post-injury. Amantadine 100-200 mg BID accelerated DRS recovery during treatment (p=0.007), but groups converged after 2-week washout. This suggests amantadine speeds recovery but may not change ultimate outcome.","disorders-of-consciousness")
B.a7J=s(["First 24 hours only","First 7 days only","First 30 days","First 2 years"],t.s)
B.aga=new A.O("AED prophylaxis has been proven effective for which duration after TBI?",B.a7J,1,"AEDs (phenytoin, levetiracetam) reduce EARLY PTS (\u22647 days) but have NOT been proven effective for preventing LATE PTS (>7 days). The Temkin trial (1990) established this. Prophylaxis beyond 1 week is not recommended.","medical-complications")
B.a5w=s(["10-15%","25-30%","40-45%","54%"],t.s)
B.aiq=new A.O("What is the incidence of DVT in TBI rehabilitation patients WITHOUT prophylaxis?",B.a5w,3,"DVT incidence without prophylaxis is approximately 54%. VTE is clinically silent in 70-80% of TBI patients, with sudden death from PE potentially being the first clinical sign. LMWH is superior to UFH for prophylaxis.","medical-complications")
B.a56=s(["3-6 months","6-12 months","12-18 months","24 months"],t.s)
B.aig=new A.O("What is the recommended timing for surgical resection of heterotopic ossification after TBI (Garland criteria)?",B.a56,2,"Garland timing: HO excision should wait 12-18 months after TBI for bone maturation (6 months after musculoskeletal injury, 12 months after SCI, 18 months after TBI). Ideal candidate: no joint pain/swelling, normal alkaline phosphatase, mature bone scan.","medical-complications")
B.a5i=s(["CN III (oculomotor)","CN VII (facial)","CN I (olfactory)","CN VIII (vestibulocochlear)"],t.s)
B.air=new A.O("Which cranial nerve is MOST commonly injured in TBI?",B.a5i,2,"CN I (olfactory) is the most commonly injured CN in TBI (~7% overall, 19.4% in moderate, 24.5% in severe). Injury occurs from tearing of olfactory filaments at the cribriform plate. It is also the only CN neuropathy present in mild TBI.","medical-complications")
B.a51=s(["Donepezil","Amantadine","Methylphenidate","Modafinil"],t.s)
B.ag0=new A.O("Which medication has the STRONGEST evidence for treating attention deficits after TBI?",B.a51,2,"Methylphenidate has the strongest evidence for improving attention and processing speed after TBI. It blocks dopamine and norepinephrine reuptake, increasing catecholamine availability. Start at 5 mg BID (morning and noon).","pharmacology")
B.a8g=s(["It lowers the seizure threshold","It causes hepatotoxicity","It blocks D2 receptors and hinders neuroplasticity/motor recovery","It causes serotonin syndrome"],t.s)
B.ahz=new A.O("Why should haloperidol be avoided in TBI patients?",B.a8g,2,"Haloperidol is a typical antipsychotic that blocks D2 dopamine receptors, which are critical for cognitive recovery and neuroplasticity after TBI. Animal studies show it hinders spatial learning and motor recovery.","pharmacology")
B.a4I=s(["Quetiapine","Methylphenidate or amantadine","Gabapentin","Lorazepam"],t.s)
B.agf=new A.O("A TBI patient presents with apathy, decreased initiation, and flat affect. SSRIs have not helped. Which medication should be considered?",B.a4I,1,"Apathy/abulia from frontal lobe injury responds better to dopaminergic agents (methylphenidate, amantadine, bromocriptine) than SSRIs. It is important to distinguish true depression from frontal lobe-mediated apathy.","pharmacology")
B.a8p=s(["Atypical antipsychotics","Benzodiazepines","Beta-blockers","Anticonvulsants"],t.s)
B.ahP=new A.O("According to the Cochrane review, which medication class has the BEST evidence for treating posttraumatic agitation?",B.a8p,2,"The Cochrane review found beta-blockers (propranolol, pindolol) have the best evidence for efficacy in treating posttraumatic agitation. Typical TBI dosing is 20-60 mg TID-QID (60-240 mg/day); the Brooke 1992 RCT titrated up to 420 mg/day. Monitor for hypotension and bradycardia (hold if HR < 60 or SBP < 90).","agitation-behavioral")
B.a6F=s(["Presence of 2 of 4 autonomic signs","Presence of 4 of 6 specified clinical features","Fever >38.5\xb0C plus tachycardia","Any combination of autonomic dysfunction"],t.s)
B.agp=new A.O("What are the diagnostic criteria for Paroxysmal Sympathetic Hyperactivity (PSH)?",B.a6F,1,"PSH requires 4 of 6: (1) fever, (2) tachycardia >120, (3) hypertension SBP >160, (4) tachypnea >30, (5) excessive diaphoresis, (6) extensor posturing/severe dystonia. Treatment: morphine + propranolol; ITB for refractory cases.","agitation-behavioral")
B.a6o=s(["Normal behavior","Mild agitation","Moderate agitation","Severe agitation"],t.s)
B.aie=new A.O("An ABS score of 32 indicates:",B.a6o,2,"ABS scoring: 14 items scored 1-4, range 14-56. \u226421: absent. 22-28: mild agitation. 29-35: moderate agitation. \u226536: severe agitation. A score of 32 falls in the moderate range.","agitation-behavioral")
B.a3E=s(["Serum sodium levels","Urine osmolality","Volume status (euvolemic vs hypovolemic)","Serum potassium levels"],t.s)
B.afA=new A.O("How do you differentiate SIADH from cerebral salt wasting (CSW)?",B.a3E,2,"Both SIADH and CSW present with hyponatremia, but the KEY difference is volume status: SIADH = euvolemic (fluid restrict), CSW = hypovolemic (give volume). Treating CSW with fluid restriction (as for SIADH) is DANGEROUS \u2014 worsens cerebral perfusion.","neuroendocrine")
B.a4z=s(["\u22645 mEq/L per 24 hours","\u226410 mEq/L per 24 hours","\u226415 mEq/L per 24 hours","\u226420 mEq/L per 24 hours"],t.s)
B.afl=new A.O("At what rate should sodium be corrected to avoid central pontine myelinolysis?",B.a4z,1,"Sodium should be corrected no more than 10 mEq/L per 24 hours to prevent central pontine myelinolysis (osmotic demyelination syndrome). This applies to correction of hyponatremia from any cause.","neuroendocrine")
B.a6O=s(["Gradual onset of symptoms over weeks","Rapid cerebral edema from impaired vascular autoregulation after a second concussion before recovery","Bilateral subdural hematomas from repeated trauma","Progressive white matter degeneration"],t.s)
B.afn=new A.O("Second impact syndrome is characterized by:",B.a6O,1,"Second impact syndrome occurs when an athlete sustains a second concussion before recovering from the first. Impaired vascular autoregulation leads to malignant cerebral edema within minutes. Morbidity approaches 100% and mortality ~50%. Most common in adolescent athletes.","concussion-mtbi")
B.a5F=s(["4 steps","5 steps","6 steps","7 steps"],t.s)
B.ahA=new A.O("How many steps are in the graduated return-to-play protocol after concussion?",B.a5F,2,"The 6-step graduated RTP protocol: (1) symptom-limited activity, (2) light aerobic exercise, (3) sport-specific exercise, (4) non-contact training drills, (5) full-contact practice (requires medical clearance), (6) return to competition. Each step takes at minimum 24 hours.","concussion-mtbi")
B.a67=s([B.agr,B.afg,B.ai8,B.ahS,B.afR,B.ai7,B.ahp,B.afb,B.ag4,B.ai3,B.ai2,B.af4,B.ahl,B.ahq,B.agX,B.agB,B.ahx,B.afS,B.agx,B.agn,B.afJ,B.afL,B.ahd,B.ag2,B.ah2,B.ai_,B.afk,B.aga,B.aiq,B.aig,B.air,B.ag0,B.ahz,B.agf,B.ahP,B.agp,B.aie,B.afA,B.afl,B.afn,B.ahA],t.e)
