B.RA=new A.c("According to the Lance definition (1980), what is the defining characteristic of spasticity?","A velocity-dependent increase in muscle tone resulting from stretch reflex hyperexcitability.")
B.Wt=new A.c("What are the four primary 'positive' features of upper motor neuron (UMN) syndrome?","Spasticity, clonus, hyperreflexia, and the Babinski sign.")
B.QV=new A.c("What are the common 'negative' features of upper motor neuron (UMN) syndrome?","Weakness, loss of dexterity, and fatigability.")
B.RC=new A.c("Approximately what percentage of patients with severe TBI develop spasticity?","70%.")
B.Xu=new A.c("What is the primary pathophysiology of spasticity at the spinal level?","Signal mishandling and a lack of inhibition of the stretch reflex from supraspinal centers.")
B.Nn=new A.c("How does spasticity assist a patient during transfers or standing?","By providing increased extensor tone in the lower extremities.")
B.Yh=new A.c("What is a potential vascular benefit of maintaining some spasticity in a paralyzed limb?","Enhanced venous return, which reduces the risk of Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT).")
B.SQ=new A.c("Before escalating medical treatment for spasticity, what is the first clinical step?","Rule out or treat exacerbating noxious stimuli (e.g., UTI, pressure injury, constipation).")
B.TN=new A.c("What does a score of 1 on the Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS) indicate?","A slight increase in tone with a catch-and-release or minimal resistance at the end of ROM.")
B.QJ=new A.c("What defines a grade of 1+ on the Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS)?","A slight increase in tone with a catch followed by minimal resistance through less than half of the ROM.")
B.T2=new A.c("What is the clinical description of a Grade 4 on the Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS)?","The affected part is rigid in flexion or extension.")
B.OJ=new A.c("What is the primary limitation of the Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS) regarding velocity?","It only measures resistance at a single velocity, failing to distinguish spasticity from contracture.")
B.UK=new A.c("According to the 2025 Movement Disorders review (Gal et al.), which scale is the only recommended clinical rating for spasticity?","The Tardieu Scale.")
B.R1=new A.c("In the Modified Tardieu Scale, what does the V1 velocity represent?","Moving the limb as slow as possible to measure passive range of motion (R2).")
B.RN=new A.c("In the Modified Tardieu Scale, what does the V3 velocity represent?","Moving the limb as fast as possible to measure the catch angle (R1).")
B.SR=new A.c("What does a large difference between R2 and R1 on the Tardieu Scale suggest?","A large dynamic component, indicating the hypertonia is mostly spasticity.")
B.Tl=new A.c("What does a small difference between R2 and R1 on the Tardieu Scale suggest?","A fixed component, indicating the hypertonia is mostly contracture.")
B.NX=new A.c("How is velocity standardized in modern Tardieu Scale protocols?","By using a metronome set to 120 bpm to guide the stretching speed.")
B.a_v=new A.c("How does spasticity differ from rigidity regarding stretch velocity?","Spasticity is velocity-dependent, whereas rigidity is constant regardless of speed.")
B.Pe=new A.c("Which form of hypertonia is characterized by a 'clasp-knife' quality?","Spasticity.")
B.OA=new A.c("Which form of hypertonia is characterized by 'lead-pipe' or 'cogwheel' resistance?","Rigidity.")
B.SF=new A.c("In which muscle groups is spasticity typically most prominent?","Antigravity muscles (upper extremity flexors and lower extremity extensors).")
B.a_r=new A.c("What maneuver is used to worsen rigidity by requesting contralateral limb movement?","The Froment maneuver.")
B.Xm=new A.c("What is the defining feature of spastic dystonia compared to pure spasticity?","The inability to fully relax the muscle even at rest, leading to spontaneous tonic contraction.")
B.P0=new A.c("What is the most common lower extremity spasticity pattern after TBI or stroke?","Equinovarus deformity.")
B.QP=new A.c("Which muscle is primarily responsible for the 'varus' (inversion) component of equinovarus?","Tibialis posterior.")
B.Y5=new A.c("What muscles are the targets for treating 'clenched fist' (thumb-in-palm) deformity?","Flexor digitorum superficialis, flexor digitorum profundus, and adductor pollicis.")
B.RJ=new A.c("What does the 'S' represent in the SOFIS management mnemonic?","Stretching and Splinting.")
B.Up=new A.c("What are the indications for serial casting in spasticity management?","Dynamic contractures with a significant spastic component (R2-R1 difference).")
B.Yi=new A.c("Why is cold therapy used as a conservative modality for spasticity?","It reduces spasticity by decreasing nerve conduction velocity.")
B.SA=new A.c("What is the mechanism of action for Baclofen (Lioresal)?","It is a presynaptic GABAB receptor agonist that inhibits the release of excitatory neurotransmitters.")
B.TI=new A.c("What is the maximum recommended daily oral dose of Baclofen?","80 mg per day.")
B.Nx=new A.c("What are the life-threatening risks of abruptly stopping oral Baclofen?","Seizures, hyperthermia, rhabdomyolysis, and multi-organ failure.")
B.WQ=new A.c("What is the mechanism of action for Tizanidine (Zanaflex)?","It is a central alpha2-adrenergic agonist that increases presynaptic inhibition of motor neurons.")
B.a_w=new A.c("What specific laboratory monitoring is required for patients taking Tizanidine?","Liver Function Tests (LFTs) due to the risk of hepatotoxicity.")
B.MQ=new A.c("Which medications should be avoided when taking Tizanidine due to drug interactions?","CYP1A2 inhibitors such as fluvoxamine or ciprofloxacin.")
B.Oo=new A.c("What is the mechanism of action for Dantrolene (Dantrium)?","It blocks calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum via the ryanodine receptor in skeletal muscle.")
B.W6=new A.c("What distinguishes Dantrolene from other oral anti-spasticity agents?","It is the only oral agent that acts peripherally on the muscle itself rather than the CNS.")
B.a_2=new A.c("Why is Diazepam generally avoided for spasticity management in TBI patients?","It causes significant sedation and negatively impacts cognitive recovery and new learning.")
B.U4=new A.c("How does Botulinum Toxin (BoNT) inhibit muscle contraction at the neuromuscular junction?","It cleaves SNARE proteins to block the presynaptic release of Acetylcholine (ACh).")
B.Px=new A.c("Which specific SNARE protein is cleaved by Botulinum Toxin Type A?","SNAP-25.")
B.Sk=new A.c("When does the peak clinical effect of a Botulinum Toxin injection typically occur?","2 to 6 weeks after injection.")
B.ZJ=new A.c("What is the primary advantage of IncobotulinumtoxinA (Xeomin) regarding immunogenicity?","It lacks complexing proteins, theoretically lowering the risk of neutralizing antibody formation.")
B.O8=new A.c("What is the preferred imaging modality for guiding Botulinum Toxin injections in 2025?","Ultrasound guidance.")
B.SC=new A.c("What is the chemical mechanism of Phenol neurolysis?","Protein denaturation leading to the destruction of nerve fibers.")
B.QU=new A.c("What is a major advantage of Phenol neurolysis over Botulinum Toxin?","It has an immediate onset of action and a longer duration (3-12 months).")
B.MI=new A.c("Which nerve is a classic target for Phenol neurolysis to treat hip adductor spasticity?","The obturator nerve.")
B.RX=new A.c("What is the primary risk when injecting Phenol into a mixed (sensory-motor) nerve?","Chronic, painful dysesthesias.")
B.YS=new A.c("How does the dosage of intrathecal baclofen compare to oral baclofen?","The intrathecal dose is typically 100 times less than the oral dose.")
B.Y6=new A.c("What condition is a specific indication for Intrathecal Baclofen (ITB) in the TBI population?","Paroxysmal Sympathetic Hyperactivity (PSH), also known as sympathetic storming.")
B.XP=new A.c("What are the early signs of Intrathecal Baclofen (ITB) withdrawal?","Severe rebound spasticity, hyperthermia, and altered mental status.")
B.P8=new A.c("What are the first-line emergency medications used to manage ITB withdrawal?","High-dose oral/enteral baclofen, IV benzodiazepines, and IV dantrolene.")
B.Tu=new A.c("What are the typical symptoms of an Intrathecal Baclofen (ITB) overdose?","Flaccidity, respiratory depression, and coma.")
B.RZ=new A.c("At what point post-injury should surgical tendon lengthening be considered for contracture?","Generally delayed 6 to 12 months post-injury to allow for spontaneous neurological recovery.")
B.VS=new A.c("During which period does the most rapid motor recovery occur after a TBI?","The first 0 to 3 months.")
B.Nk=new A.c("What is the strongest predictor of motor recovery in the IMPACT prognostic model?","The GCS motor component.")
B.Vf=new A.c("How does the duration of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) relate to motor outcomes?","Longer durations of PTA are associated with worse motor and functional outcomes.")
B.Qa=new A.c("What principle of neuroplasticity states that practice must be personally meaningful to the patient?","Salience.")
B.Vd=new A.c("What is the primary methodology of Constraint-Induced Movement Therapy (CIMT)?","Restraining the unaffected limb to force repetitive use of the affected limb.")
B.W0=new A.c("What is the intended clinical target for selective dorsal rhizotomy (SDR)?","Selective sectioning of dorsal nerve rootlets to reduce spasticity.")
B.N1=new A.c("What is the specific target of Gabapentin (Neurontin) in the nervous system?","The alpha2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels.")
B.ON=new A.c("Which oral anti-spasticity medication also serves as the treatment for malignant hyperthermia?","Dantrolene.")
B.OT=new A.c("What is the 'clasp-knife' phenomenon?","A sudden release in resistance after an initial 'catch' during passive muscle stretch.")
B.Z1=new A.c("Which muscle is typically targeted to treat forearm pronation spasticity?","Pronator teres or pronator quadratus.")
B.Sw=new A.c("In TBI recovery, what does a transition from an 'unfavorable' to 'favorable' outcome mean?","Improvement in functional status, often measured by the Glasgow Outcome Scale.")
B.Z_=new A.c("What is the purpose of the 'Y' component in the Modified Tardieu Scale?","It records the specific angle at which the catch or clonus occurs.")
B.Op=new A.c("What is the clinical significance of a Quality score of 4 on the Modified Tardieu Scale?","Infatigable clonus lasting more than 10 seconds.")
B.Td=new A.c("Why is the incidence of neutralizing antibodies a concern with Botulinum Toxin Type A?","It leads to secondary non-response where the patient no longer benefits from the injections.")
B.XV=new A.c("What is the function of split anterior tibialis tendon transfer (SPLATT)?","To redirect muscle force to correct equinovarus deformity.")
B.YM=new A.c("Which UMN phenomenon involves the inability to relax a muscle at rest without an external stretch?","Spastic dystonia.")
B.VZ=new A.c("How frequently are serial casts typically changed in a spasticity protocol?","Every 5 to 7 days.")
B.Vo=new A.c("What is the 'Neurogenic' vs 'Biomechanical' distinction in instrumented spasticity measurement?","The separation of active reflex activity (neural) from passive tissue stiffness (biomechanical).")
B.Rz=new A.c("What is a significant contraindication for serial casting?","Peripheral Vascular Disease (PVD) or severe edema.")
B.S1=new A.c("Which SNARE protein is targeted by Botulinum Toxin Type B?","VAMP/synaptobrevin.")
B.Zh=new A.c("What is the typical battery lifespan for an implanted ITB pump?","5 to 7 years.")
B.V0=new A.c("What is the time frame for a positive response during an ITB trial bolus?","Significant reduction in spasticity within 4 to 8 hours of the bolus.")
B.SK=new A.c("Which neuroplasticity principle emphasizes that rehabilitation should begin as soon as possible?","Timing.")
B.Ov=new A.c("What allele is associated with poorer recovery and reduced neuroplasticity after TBI?","ApoE4.")
B.Ni=new A.c("What emerging technology uses electrical currents to assist task-oriented motor training?","Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS).")
B.SD=new A.c("What defines 'equinus' in the context of an ankle deformity?","Fixed or dynamic plantarflexion, primarily caused by gastrocnemius-soleus spasticity.")
B.YP=new A.c("Which medication acts as an alpha2-adrenergic agonist and may cause rebound hypertension if stopped abruptly?","Tizanidine.")
B.OX=new A.c("Which muscles are responsible for shoulder internal rotation and adduction spasticity?","Pectoralis major, subscapularis, and latissimus dorsi.")
B.Rs=new A.c("What is the 'catch angle' (R1) in the Tardieu scale?","The joint angle where a sudden resistance to fast stretch is first felt.")
B.OR=new A.c("How does robot-assisted rehabilitation support neuroplasticity?","Through precise, highly repetitive, and controlled motor exercises.")
