B.afN=new A.O("Which oral antispasticity agent requires baseline and periodic monitoring of Liver Function Tests (LFTs) due to the risk of hepatotoxicity?",B.a5Z,1,"Tizanidine, a central alpha-2 adrenergic agonist, is known to potentially cause liver injury and requires LFT monitoring at 1, 3, and 6 months.","spasticity-motor")
B.a4p=s(["Agonism of GABAB receptors in the spinal cord","Inhibition of calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum via the ryanodine receptor","Cleavage of SNAP-25 proteins to prevent ACh release at the neuromuscular junction","Blockade of voltage-gated sodium channels in the peripheral nerve"],t.s)
B.agO=new A.O("What is the primary mechanism of action for Dantrolene in the treatment of spasticity?",B.a4p,1,"Dantrolene acts peripherally on the skeletal muscle itself, directly interfering with the excitation-contraction coupling.","spasticity-motor")
B.aar=s(["Baclofen overdose","Intrathecal Baclofen withdrawal","Serotonin syndrome","Autonomic dysreflexia"],t.s)
B.afo=new A.O("A patient with an Intrathecal Baclofen (ITB) pump presents with a fever of 41degreesC, severe rebound spasticity, and altered mental status. Which condition should be the primary concern?",B.aar,1,"Sudden cessation of ITB can lead to a life-threatening syndrome featuring hyperthermia, rhabdomyolysis, and autonomic instability.","spasticity-motor")
B.a6S=s(["Musculocutaneous nerve","Obturator nerve","Tibial nerve","Femoral nerve"],t.s)
B.ahf=new A.O("Which muscle is a primary target for chemical neurolysis with phenol to treat hip adductor spasticity that interferes with perineal hygiene?",B.a6S,1,"Phenol injections to the motor branches of the obturator nerve effectively reduce hip adductor tone to facilitate hygiene and positioning.","spasticity-motor")
B.a8H=s(["Slight increase in tone manifested by a catch-and-release at the end of the range of motion","Slight increase in tone manifested by a catch, followed by minimal resistance through less than half of the range of motion","Marked increase in tone through most of the range of motion, but the affected part is easily moved","Considerable increase in tone where passive movement is difficult"],t.s)
B.ai0=new A.O("On the Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS), how is a grade of 1+ defined?",B.a8H,1,"This specific description distinguishes 1+ from both the simpler grade 1 and the more moderate grade 2.","spasticity-motor")
B.a7o=s(["Oral baclofen and stretching","Botulinum toxin A (BoNT-A) and serial casting","Phenol neurolysis and TENS","Intrathecal baclofen and tendon lengthening surgery"],t.s)
B.afT=new A.O("Which combination of treatments has been shown in a 2019 RCT to be more effective than individual therapies for treating ankle equinus?",B.a7o,1,"Combining chemodenervation to relax the muscle with serial casting to provide prolonged stretch yields superior results in improving dorsiflexion.","spasticity-motor")
B.a5v=s(["Hyperactive deep tendon reflexes","Resistance that worsens with contralateral movement (Froment maneuver)","A 'clasp-knife' phenomenon during passive stretch","Preferential involvement of the antigravity muscles"],t.s)
B.ag7=new A.O("In the differential diagnosis of hypertonia, which feature is highly suggestive of rigidity rather than spasticity?",B.a5v,1,"Rigidity is often enhanced by performing a task with the opposite limb, whereas spasticity is typically unaffected by this.","spasticity-motor")
B.a9O=s(["OnabotulinumtoxinA (Botox)","AbobotulinumtoxinA (Dysport)","IncobotulinumtoxinA (Xeomin)","RimabotulinumtoxinB (Myobloc)"],t.s)
B.ags=new A.O("Which botulinum toxin formulation is unique for having no complexing proteins, potentially lowering the risk of neutralizing antibody formation?",B.a9O,2,"Xeomin is a pure 150 kDa neurotoxin that has been processed to remove all extraneous complexing proteins.","spasticity-motor")
B.a8b=s(["Within the first 3 months to maximize early neuroplasticity","At least 1 year post-injury to allow for a neurological plateau","Only after 24 months when all potential motor gains have ceased","Immediately after the first failed dose of oral Baclofen"],t.s)
B.af6=new A.O("What is the recommended timing for considering an Intrathecal Baclofen (ITB) pump implantation following a Traumatic Brain Injury?",B.a8b,1,"Waiting 12 months ensures that the patient's spontaneous recovery has stabilized before committing to a permanent implant.","spasticity-motor")
B.a3w=s(["Iliopsoas and Medial Hamstrings","Gastrocnemius, Soleus, and Tibialis Posterior","Quadriceps and Peroneus Longus","Gluteus Maximus and Tibialis Anterior"],t.s)
B.ahk=new A.O("Equinovarus, the most common lower extremity spasticity pattern, typically involves which group of muscles?",B.a3w,1,"The gastroc-soleus complex causes plantarflexion (equinus) and the tibialis posterior causes inversion (varus).","spasticity-motor")
B.a6d=s(["10%","38%","70%","None; recovery effectively plateaus at 1 year"],t.s)
